summary:
It always starts the same way.
A user types:
&ldquo;What&rsquo;s the best multivitamin for women in their 30s?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Healthiest soda alternative?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Best travel insurance for a family trip to Italy?&rdquo;
But they don&rsquo;t click a search result. They don&rsquo;t scroll through 10 blue links. They ask ChatGPT, Perplexity, or Gemini, and they get a confident, summarized answer.
If your brand isn&rsquo;t mentioned in that response, you don&rsquo;t exist in that moment.

It always starts the same way. A campaign wraps, and the team pulls up the performance report. The click-through rate? Above benchmark. CPM? 30% lower than the platform average. There&rsquo;s a general sense of relief, maybe even celebration. Everyone&rsquo;s nodding. Job well done. But then someone asks the one question that doesn&rsquo;t show up on the dashboard: &ldquo;Did it actually drive anything?&rdquo;
That&rsquo;s when things get murky.
Benchmarks: The Rental Tux That Sort of Fits Benchmarks have become a go-to comfort metric in media analytics.

Stop Asking for Data You&rsquo;ll Never Use The Real Problem Isn&rsquo;t the Dashboard. It&rsquo;s How We Treat Data as a Checklist, Not a Conversation.
Analytics teams are constantly asked for everything: &ldquo;Can you pull media spend, website traffic, sales lift, creative performance, even click text and session duration?&rdquo;
And they deliver. Hours go into cleaning data, joining tables, building charts, uploading decks, and updating dashboards ‚Äî most of which barely get used.

